entry.title: Lacros-Test: Skip crosapi version check if already supported in ash.
entry.content:
This is a follow up cl for crrev.com/c/5117919.



Due to an issue with some tests improperly calling

BrowserInitParams::SetInitParamsForTests in test

Setup() which wipes out interceface_versions data

in BrowserInitParams, when IsTestControllerAvailable()

is called in browser_test_util to check if a TestControl

method is supported in ash, it failed incorrectly(the method is

available in all ash channels). This issue blocks another pending cl(crrev.com/c/5068434) since it calls browser_test_util::WaitForWindowCreation from

InProcessBrowserTest:: PreRunTestOnMainThread() and will

failed in IsTestControllerAvailable() for those tests which

wipes out BrowserInitParams::interface_versions by calling BrowserInitParams::SetInitParamsForTests. There

is already an ongoing effort to fix the root cause of

BrowserInitParams::SetInitParamsForTests issue, but it will

take some time to land that cl.



As a workaround to unblock crrev.com/c/5068434, this cl

removes the code for handling version skew if

the crosapi method already supported by all ash channels.

Instead, we validate if TestController is available in

LacrosService before calling crosapi. When test code calls

the apis in browser_test_utils to wait for UI elements to be

created in ash, ash should be available. If ash is not available

for some reason, it may expose some real problem to be fixed.

This should be handled differently than the cases in which

the crosapi is not supported in ash or the operation times out

(The existing code returns false for all these cases). Now the functions

fail with CHECK if ash is not available, and return false if crosapi

is not supported by ash or times out.



I patched crrev.com/c/5068434 with this cl and it passes CQ

run(crrev.com/c/5121452).

that the SharedImage needs GL check for SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2 being

in the value. This effectively checks that SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLE2_READ

and SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2_WRITE are *both* specified. This is not

neither value. However, in the future clients will sometimes pass one

or the other value. This CL changes these checks to check for *either*

in the given SharedImageUsage.

entry.title: Add CHECK to AXPlatformNodeWin::InternalRelease to detect double-free
entry.content:
This CL adds a CHECK in AXPlatformNodeWin::InternalRelease that tests

whether the instance's memory can be freed from an external COM client. I think that it's possible in theory, but would like to see

some crashes in the wild to confirm it.



The theory is this:

1. An AXFragmentRootPlatformNodeWin ComPtr is created upon creation of

an AXFragmentRootWin (the member `platform_node_`). At that point, the

refcount is 1.

2. A COM client, presumably an assistive technology, gets a reference

to that ComPtr. The refcount at this point is 2.

3. The COM client releases the ComPtr more than once, mistakenly,

freeing the memory associated with this ComPtr. (refcount = 0)

4. Since `platform_node_` only gets nullified (ie., = nullptr) when

the AXFragmentRootWin is destroyed, the `platform_node_` is not nullptr

at line 5051 in AXPlatformNodeWin::Navigate, so we get into the `if`.

5. At line 5060, we try to access the memory in the pointer that got

freed and it crashes.



This CL introduces a new member `destroy_was_called_` only set to true

when AXPlatformNodeWin::Destroy (and therefore the subclass

AXFragmentRootPlatformNodeWin) is called. We set it before the ComPtr

is released again (see `Dispose`), so the CHECK should always pass if

the refcount only reaches 0 after the internal reference to the

platform node is nullified.

entry.title: Use WAL mode on UkmDatabase
entry.content:
This CL is switching the journal mode of segmentation database to

use WAL (Write-Ahead Logging). Instead of using a journal file

which contains a rollback with the original data (database-journal),

the database will have a Write-Ahead Logging which contains the modifications. Modifications are merge into the original on a snapshot.



see: Write-Ahead Logging (https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)



The main advantage of using WAL is a reduction in the amount

of disk flushes by SQL write.

entry.title: DOM: Observable EventTarget integration 1/N
entry.content:
This CL implements "limited" and "leaky" EventTarget integration with

the Observable API. See below for what "limited" and "leaky" mean.

Concretely, this involves introducing the `on()` method to the

EventTarget interface, so that all EventTargets can return Observables

that listen for events. This is the part that really makes Observables a

"better addEventListener()".



This is the first instance of a natively-constructed Observable, as

opposed to a JS-constructed Observable. This means the subscription

callback passed to the Observable constructor is not just a JS callback

function with user-defined code, but instead is a C++ delegate class,

called `SubscribeDelegate` which has its first concrete implementation

provided by EventTarget (in event_target.cc). The concrete

implementation of this interface that this CL introduces, adds an event

listener to the given EventTarget, upon subscription. The events are

forwarded to the Subscriber's `next()` method. This is what unlocks

more ergonomic event handling with the composable Observable primitive

and all of its (coming) operators.



1. The EventTarget integration is considered "limited" because we do not

support any of the `AddEventListenerOptions` yet, as of this CL. A

subsequent CL will add support for a more restricted version of the

`AddEventListenerOptions`, called `ObservableEventListenerOptions`,

which does not include a `once` option, or an `AbortSignal`, since

Observable operators and subscription is responsible for managing those

aspects. Concretely, an `ObservableEventListenerOptions` will

resolve to an `AddEventListenerOptionsResolved` accordingly. See:

- https://github.com/WICG/observable/issues/66

- https://github.com/WICG/observable/pull/67

- https://github.com/WICG/observable/issues/65



2. The EventTarget integration is considered "leaky" as of this CL,

because there is currently no way to remove an event listener added by

an EventTarget-vended Observable. This will come in a subsequent CL,

which will pass the test that is currently failing in this CL. See

https://github.com/WICG/observable/issues/75 for discussion about

tying the subscription termination to removing an event listener.

From a technical perspective, this is pretty easy — it involves adding

an abort algorithm to `Subscriber#signal` (which has already been wired

up properly by now!) that removes the given per-Subscription

`ObservableEventListener` NativeEventListener from the associated

EventTarget. That implementation has already been sketched out in

https://crrev.com/c/4262153 and the design doc. It will included in a

follow-up CL, to reduce the complexity of this one.

entry.title: Check if RaceNetworkRequest is aborted before committing responses
entry.content:
`state_` in ServiceWorkerRaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient can be

transitioned to State::kAborted when writing the response data to

another data pipe has failed, which basically means the preload network

request has failed.



On the other hand, in-flight preload requests are reused as fallback

requests if the fetch handler result is a network fallback. Before this

CL, when the preload request is dispatched and the fetch handler result

is fallback, the preload request was used as a fallback regardless of

its `state_` even if that was aborted. After this CL, the preload

request is used as a fallback only when the |state_| is not aborted.



This may introduce additional network request though, obviously it's

better than returning the error response. The network request triggered

here is the one which the ServiceWorker normally use. So it doesn't

involve a special data pipe handling thus more reliable than the preload

request.

entry.content:
FakeOmniboxView is now constraints by layout constraints only. Frame

positioning is not used anymore, therefore, the view is always at the

right place even when the window is resized (on iPad only) or the font

size is changed.

This patch also makes sure the new FakeOmniboxView is always added to

the view, even when it has to be hidden (in landscape mode, for iPhone).

So when the user rotates back to portrait mode, the latest

FakeOmniboxView is shown.

And this patch makes sure the exiting FakeOmniboxView is always removed

from the superview.

entry.title: Split AutocompleteTable from AutofillTable
entry.content:
See go/splitting-autofill-table. Creates a separate AutocompleteTable

class by moving all Autocomplete related code and tests to a separate

file. The code is moved 1:1 without changes.



Like AutofillTable, it can be accessed through the a static

FromWebDatabase() getter. All callers are updated accordingly.



AutocompleteTable is a WebDatabaseTable, and as such instantiated

by WebDataServiceWrapper. Contrary to AutofillTable, which exists in

the profile and the account scoped database, AutocompleteTable only

exists in the profile scoped database. This is because the account

scoped database is only used by Payments.



AutofillTable also implements syncer::SyncMetadataStore and acts as the

SyncMetadataStore for all components/autofill related sync logic. This

is kept as is. In the Autocomplete sync bridge, AutofillTable is

referenced for everything metadata related, and AutocompleteTable for

everything non-metadata related.
